<P>Some will &s;ay, <Q>The author &s;eems to indulge <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">, and talks my&s;tically in &s;ome pages of his narrative.</Q> But let it be remembered, that men of great piety, who&s;e &s;ouls are moulded into a temper of religion, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">choic the truths of the go&s;pel in a glorious and tran&s;cendent degree of divine light; they live under warm im|pre&s;&s;ions of the&s;e truths, and feel the &s;weet influence of them on <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> the powers of nature: This m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters">s them &s;peak even of the mo&s;t ra|tions things of religion, &s;ometimes in the language of an inward &s;en&s;ation, of which divine reli&s;h and favour per&s;ons of lower degrees of prety feel <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> little, and the irreligious man knows nothing at all.</P>
