<P>To a gentlewoman he &s;aid, I long for his &s;alvation; I ble&s;s his name I have found him, I am taken up in ble&s;|&s;ing him, I am dying rojoicing in the Lord. Well, &s;aid but, I long to be in promi&s;ed land. <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">He, apprehending him&s;elf very low, &s;aid, Here I die, &s;aying. Lord Je&s;us receive my &s;pirit.&mdash;Come, &s;weet Lord Je&s;us, receive this &s;pirit fluttering within my brea&s;t, like a bird so be out of a &s;hare.&mdash;When will I hear him &s;ays, <HI>Ari&s;t, my love, my fair one, and come away, the win|ter is pa&s;t, the rain is gone over,</HI> &amp;c. Come &s;weet Lord Je&s;us, come and take me by the hand, that I &s;tumble not in the dark valley of death. One &s;aid, He has been plea&s;ed to &s;et his love upon you, and he will help through in this la&s;t conflict; for his word is &s;till the &s;ame, <HI>I will never, never leave, nor for&s;ake you; he is able to &s;ave to the n<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">ermo&s;t.</HI> He an&s;wered, I know that.</P>
